# Next.js & TypeScript Conventions

## Types

- Use explicit types everywhere; avoid `any`
- Define domain types in a shared `types/` directory
- Validate all external input (API, forms, params) with Zod schemas

## Components

- Functional components only
- Colocate component-specific logic; extract shared logic into hooks
- Keep components small and composable
- Use Tailwind for styling — no CSS modules unless justified

## Project Structure

- `app/` — Next.js App Router pages and layouts
- `components/` — reusable UI components
- `lib/` — domain logic, Supabase client, utilities
- `types/` — shared TypeScript types and Zod schemas
- `config/` — business rule configuration (role-balanced styles, penalty amounts, etc.)

## Data & Validation

- All mutations go through server actions or API routes
- Validate with Zod on the server side before any DB write
- Keep Supabase queries in `lib/` — never call Supabase directly from components
